{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570099"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:37:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:37:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22684"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22684"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.08,0.13,0.55,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15631"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111560"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15631"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22684"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93649"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"7940"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45374"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45379"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111560"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-day history of increasing pain and swelling of his left lower leg after he scratched an insect bite in that area. He reports local warmth and tenderness but no fevers, rigors, nausea or systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus. His body mass index is 31 kg/m2. His regular medication is metformin. He does not smoke and drinks about two glasses of wine a day. He works as a landscaper and wears shorts most days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 118/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. The left mid-shin area is the only apparent abnormality (Image). There is no crepitus on palpation.  Peripheral pulses are palpable and there is no lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying pathological process?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cellulitis","Lymphangitis","Necrotising fasciitis","Erysipelas","Impetigo"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe changes in the photograph show a bright erythematous, tender plaque with a clearly raised, well-demarcated edge and mild oedema; there is no crepitus, bullae or skin necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythematous lower limb infections span a spectrum from superficial to deep tissue involvement. Distinguishing features on examination guide diagnosis and urgency. Erysipelas involves the upper dermis and superficial lymphatics, producing a bright red, tender plaque with a raised, sharply demarcated border, often following a minor skin break. Cellulitis spreads within the deeper dermis and subcutaneous tissue, leading to more diffuse, ill-defined margins and less prominent elevation of the lesion. Rapidly progressive severe pain, systemic toxicity, bullae or skin necrosis suggest deeper necrotising infection requiring urgent surgical review.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely because it typically presents with diffuse erythema and oedema that blend into surrounding skin with poorly defined borders, reflecting involvement of the deeper dermis and subcutaneous tissue; in the stem the margin is raised and sharply demarcated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphangitis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with red linear streaks tracking proximally from a primary skin focus towards regional lymph nodes and tender nodal enlargement; the stem describes a circumscribed plaque without proximal streaking or tender lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENecrotising fasciitis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given the absence of severe pain out of proportion, systemic toxicity, skin anaesthesia, bullae, crepitus or rapidly progressive necrosis; examination shows a localised raised edge rather than signs of deep fascial involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErysipelas\u003C/strong\u003E best fits the described raised, bright erythematous plaque with a well-demarcated edge after a minor breach in skin, consistent with infection of the upper dermis and superficial lymphatics, most commonly due to streptococci.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpetigo\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with superficial crusted erosions or honey-coloured crusts, often peri-oral or on exposed areas, and not with a single tender plaque with sharply circumscribed raised margins as described.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erysipelas presents with an acutely tender, erythematous plaque with sharply raised, well-demarcated borders due to infection of the upper dermis and superficial lymphatics.","Cellulitis involves deeper dermis and subcutaneous tissue with diffuse, ill-defined margins and a less raised edge.","Early recognition of well-demarcated margins helps distinguish erysipelas from cellulitis and guides appropriate antimicrobial therapy targeting streptococci."],"references":["Clebak KT, Malone MA. Skin Infections. Prim Care Clin Office Pract 2018; 45:433\u201354. Available from: https://www.primarycare.theclinics.com/article/S0095-4543(18)30041-1/fulltext","DermNet\u00ae [Internet]. 2023 [cited 2025 Aug 16]. Erysipelas. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/erysipelas"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93649"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22684"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22041"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22041"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/NMcmOZliz2nWT6XFkyc1UO1j3CWfih.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/NMcmOZliz2nWT6XFkyc1UO1j3CWfih.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93649"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-16T21:32:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-16T21:33:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15631"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111560"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms"